05110nam a22006375i 9780520382220DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203822207 a10.1525/97805203822202doi  a(DE-B1597)617177  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDD78.B55bP37 2023 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.896043/155223/eng/202205191 aPartridge, Damani J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlackness as a Universal Claim :bHolocaust Heritage, Noncitizen Futures, and Black Power in Berlin /cDamani J. Partridge. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (238 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Occuping Blackness -- t1. After Diaspora, Beyond Citizenship -- t2. Exploding Hitler and Americanizing Germany: Occupying Black Bodies and Postwar Desire -- t3. Occupying American Blackness and Reconfiguring European Spaces: Noncitizen Articulations in Berlin and Beyond -- tPart II. Holocaust Memory and Exclusionary Democracy -- t4. Holocaust Mahnmal (Memorial): Monumental Memory amid Contemporary Race -- t5. Democratization as Exclusion: Noncitizen Futures, Holocaust Heritage, and the Defunding of Refugee Participation -- tPart III. Noncitizen Futures -- t6. The Rehearsal Is the Revolution: “Insurrectionary Imagination” -- t7. Articulating a Noncitizen Politics: Nation-State Pity versus Black Possibility -- tConclusion: From Claiming Blackness to Black Liberation -- tKey Terms and Sites -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this bold and provocative new book, Damani Partridge examines the possibilities and limits for a universalized Black politics. German youth of Turkish, Arab, and African descent use claims of Blackness to hold states and other institutions accountable for racism today. Partridge tracks how these young people take on the expressions of Black Power, acting out the scene from the 1968 Olympics, proclaiming ";I am Malcolm X,"; expressing mutual struggle with Muhammad Ali and Spike Lee, and standing with raised and clenched fists next to Angela Davis. Partridge also documents public school teachers, federal program leaders, and politicians demanding that young immigrants account for the global persistence of anti-Semitism as part of the German state's commitment to anti-genocidal education. He uses these stories to interrogate the relationships between European Enlightenment, Holocaust memory, and Black futures, showing how noncitizens work to reshape their everyday lives. In doing so, he demonstrates how Blackness is a concept that energizes, inspires, and makes possible participation beyond national belonging for immigrants, refugees, Black people, and other People of Color.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aBlack peoplexPolitical activityzGermanyzBerlin. 0aBlack powerzGermanyzBerlin. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xInfluence. 0aNoncitizensxPolitical activityzGermanyzBerlin. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022 Englishz978311099455108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022z9783110994520oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076649340uhttps://doi.org